After experimenting with different data splits and analysing the results, the conclusion is that, ideally, the model should be trained on 
enough data which allows it to reliably learn its main (true) patterns, but not too much data that it starts to overfit. When the model’s 
performance is being evaluated, the validation and test sets should contain enough data for the results to be meaningful and reliable.

Thus, a 60:20:20 split ratio is more balanced than a 70:15:15 split ratio and strikes the best balance which avoids both underfitting and overfitting, 
which makes it achieve great generalisation (i.e. the model achieves consistent accuracy when evaluating many different, unseen data sets).
